{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17493436","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17493436"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T07:11:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T07:11:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1325"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1325","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1325"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.51,0.15,0.22,0.06,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1325"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109880"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1325","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1325"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1325"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92241"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"163"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"9051"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7951"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8014"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13424"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13973"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14356"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39845"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41197"},{"type":"contributions","id":"47005"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109880","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109880"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with severe pain and swelling in multiple finger joints that woke her from sleep six hours ago. She has had three previous episodes affecting her toes and knee over the past two years which resolved with simple analgesia. Her medical history includes hypertension treated with hydrochlorothiazide. She drinks eight standard drinks of wine per week and does not smoke.  She wants definitive treatment to prevent further painful episodes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 82/min, blood pressure 145/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Her body mass index is 32 kg/m2. Multiple finger joints are warm, erythematous, and exquisitely tender with visible tophi. There are no signs of infection or trauma.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Colchicine plus allopurinol","Prednisolone","Celecoxib","Febuxostat plus prednisolone","Intra-articular corticosteroid injection"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with an acute polyarticular gout flare with evidence of chronic disease (tophi). The presentation is typical with nocturnal onset, severe pain, and multiple risk factors including thiazide diuretic use, obesity, and alcohol consumption.  Treatment is determined by co-morbidities, cost, potential drug-interactions and patient preference.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EColchicine plus allopurinol\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate initial treatment. Current guidelines support starting both acute treatment (colchicine) and long-term urate-lowering therapy (allopurinol) simultaneously, provided prophylaxis is given. This is a change from previous recommendations which suggested waiting until the acute flare resolved before starting allopurinol. The presence of tophi indicates chronic disease requiring urgent urate-lowering therapy for acute and chronic treatment simultaneously.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrednisolone\u003C/strong\u003E alone, while effective for acute flares, does not address the need for long-term urate-lowering therapy in this patient with chronic gout. It may be particularly useful in patients who cannot tolerate colchicine or have contraindications to NSAIDs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECelecoxib, a non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drug,\u003C/strong\u003E carry significant risks in elderly patients including gastrointestinal bleeding and acute kidney injury. While effective for acute flares, they do not address the need for long-term management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFebuxostat plus prednisolone\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate if allopurinol was contraindicated or not tolerated, but allopurinol remains first-line therapy for urate-lowering.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntra-articular corticosteroid injection\u003C/strong\u003E is most appropriate for monoarticular gout. This patient has polyarticular involvement making systemic therapy more appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key principles of management include immediate relief of the acute flare (with colchicine), prevention of future attacks (with allopurinol), and modification of risk factors (weight loss, reducing alcohol intake, considering alternative antihypertensive therapy). Modern evidence supports starting allopurinol during acute flares at a low dose (100mg daily) with gradual up-titration to achieve a serum urate target below 0.36 mmol/L.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["First-line treatment for acute gout flares includes colchicine plus initiation of allopurinol with prophylaxis","Modern guidelines support starting allopurinol during acute flares, contrary to previous recommendations to wait until resolution","Risk factors for gout include thiazide diuretics, obesity, alcohol consumption, and being post-menopausal"],"references":["Robinson PC, Stamp LK. The management of gout: much has changed. Australian family physician. 2016 May;45(5):299-302."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92241"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1325"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18996"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18996","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18996"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/e35df4fa-d6ef-49d6-a071-c1c132b971e1.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/e35df4fa-d6ef-49d6-a071-c1c132b971e1.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":513,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92241","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92241"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-27T13:02:08+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-27T13:05:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1325"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109880"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":